HEADWORD: Refugee
<hw>Ref`u*gee"</hw> <pr>(r?f`?*j?")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧fugi⟦eacute⟧</ets>, fr. <ets>se r⟦eacute⟧fugier</ets> to
take refuge. See <er>Refuge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who flees to a shelter, or place of safety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Especially, one who, in times of persecution or
political commotion, flees to a foreign power or country for safety;
<as>as, the French <ex>refugees</ex> who left France after the
revocation of the edict of Nantes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

